AB  - IntroductionLitterfall is essential in tropical forests, providing nutrients and supporting nutrient cycling through decomposition. During ecological restoration, nutrient cycling rates typically align with forest succession, yet the influence of forest development on nutrient return via litterfall remains unclear. This uncertainty arises from seasonal and local variations in litter dynamics within restored forests.ObjectivesWe aimed to determine how the litter production and nutrient return to the soil have been recovered in forests undergoing restoration compared to remnants.MethodsWe studied tropical riparian forests at different restoration stages, approximately 10 years (older restored forests; ORF) and approximately 5 years (younger restored forests; YRF), and remnants to evaluate seasonality in litterfall and leaf litter nutrient concentrations. The study was conducted in seasonal semideciduous forests in southeastern Brazil, characterized by wet and dry periods. We sampled litterfall monthly and determined nutrient concentrations of accumulated leaf litter at 3-month intervals to characterize wet and dry periods.ResultsLitter production peaked at the end of the dry season, with a minor peak at the beginning of the wet season, a trend more pronounced in remnants and ORF. Leaf litter nutrient concentrations fluctuated seasonally, with lower nitrogen (N), potassium, and magnesium and higher calcium and C:N values at the end of the dry season, indicating nutrient resorption, particularly N. While nutrient return via leaf litter was similar between remnants and ORF, it was lower in YRF, primarily due to reduced litter production.ConclusionsOur findings indicate that after a decade, nutrient return in tropical riparian forests has been restored, contributing to nutrient cycling recovery.
