AB  - Nucleation has been introduced as a promising method for ecological restoration and represents an efficient, as well as economical, alternative to existing methods of restoration to accelerate secondary succession in degraded sites. In this study, we evaluated ecological indicators of taxonomic diversity and functional diversity of planted trees and subsequent natural regeneration individuals to verify the success of restoration in three sites (Cacapava do Sul, Minas do Leao, and Pantano Grande) with applied nucleation carried out seven years ago in Rio Grande do Sul State, in south of Brazil. All shrub and tree regenerating or planted individuals with a height greater than 30 cm were counted, identified, and measured in 5 m x 5 m plots, totaling 575 m(2) evaluated in each site. The results show that richness of regenerating species was similar in each site, but the richness of planted species was lower in Minas do Leao, intermediate in Cacapava do Sul, and higher in Pantano Grande. We verify a difference in the floristic composition of planted and regenerating species. The functional diversity indices were similar between planted and regenerating, with the exception of functional dispersion, although Minas do Leao presents low functional richness (0.13). This indicates that even with lower species richness and lower functional richness in planting does not imply lower species richness and lower functional richness of regenerants. Applied nucleation can be an efficient method for ecological restoration and favors the micro-habitat alteration and the return of propagules, even with lower initial richness of planted species.
